Getting started with the Comparative Legislators Database

The Comparative Legislators Database (CLD) includes political, sociodemographic, career, online presence, public attention, and visual information for over 45,000 contemporary and historical politicians from ten countries (see the corresponding article for more information). It can be accessed via legislatoR - an R package that is available on both CRAN and GitHub.

Before you start with the following tasks, skim the tutorial to make yourself familiar with the database. You find it here.

For the following tasks, you will work with ONE of the legislatures. The legislature youll work with depends on your first name:

Your first name starts with Legislature Code
A-C Austrian Nationalrat aut
D-F Canadian House of Commons can
G-I Czech Poslanecka Snemovna cze
J-L Spanish Congreso de los Diputados esp
M-O French Assemble fra
P-R German Bundestag deu
S-U Irish Dail irl
V-X UK House of Commons gbr
Y-Z US House of Representatives usa_house

The following tasks will be based on data from the core and political tables of the database.

  1. Create a new variable age_at_death that reports the age at which legislators died. Then, plot the distribution of that variable for the entire dataset.
aut_core <- aut_core %>%
  mutate(
    birth = as.Date(birth, format = "%Y-%m-%d"), 
    death = as.Date(death, format = "%Y-%m-%d"), 
    age_at_death = as.numeric(difftime(death, birth, units = "auto")),
    age_at_death = age_at_death / 365
  )

ggplot(aut_core, aes(x = age_at_death)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, fill = "blue", color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Figure 1: Distribution of Age at Death of Legislators in Austria",
    x = "Age at Death (Years)",
    y = "Frequency"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

# One notices an outlier, Friedrich Schmidt, who apparently died at age 125. Upon double checking the information on his death, this is wrong. Mr Schmidt died in 1943 at age 69.
  1. What is the most frequent birthday in your sample (e.g., January 15)?
aut_core <- aut_core %>%
  mutate(
    birth = as.Date(birth, format = "%Y-%m-%d"), 
    birth_month_day = format(birth, format = "%m-%d")
  )

birth_month_day_counts <- table(aut_core$birth_month_day)

most_frequent_birth_month_day <- names(birth_month_day_counts[birth_month_day_counts == max(birth_month_day_counts)])

# The most frequent birthday appears to be January 1st. However, January 1st is often put down in birth certificates, when the actual date of birth is unknown. Hence, I will explore the second most frequent birthday now. 

sorted_counts <- sort(birth_month_day_counts, decreasing = TRUE)

second_most_frequent_birth_month_day <- names(sorted_counts)[2]

1923/365
[1] 5.268493
# The second most frequent birthday is November 3rd. While we observe January 1st 25 times, we observe November 3rd 15 times. We can assume that birthdays are, not perfectly but sufficiently well, equally distributed throughout the year. We should thus see every date represented about 5 times. January 1st being the birthday of 25 observations thus seems highly unlikely. At the same time observing November 3rd 15 times also appears to be rather unlikely, but one could still make the case that this falls under the variation that is to be expected. To summarize, theoretically the most frequent birthday is January 1st, but practically rather November 3rd.
  1. Generate a table that provides the 5 legislators with the longest names (in terms of number of characters, ignoring whitespace).
aut_core <- aut_core %>%
  mutate(name_length = nchar(gsub(" ", "", name)))

top_longest_names <- aut_core %>%
  arrange(desc(name_length)) %>%
  head(5)

table_top_longest_names <- top_longest_names %>%
  select(name, name_length) %>%
  kable("html") %>%
  kable_styling() %>%
  add_header_above(c("Table 1: The 5 Austrian Legislators with the Longest Names" = 2))

# The longest names are: Johannes Schauer-Schoberlechner, Elisabeth Kaufmann-Bruckberger, Katharina Cortolezis-Schlager, Daniela Holzinger-Vogtenhuber and Douglas Hoyos-Trauttmansdorff.


Task 2 - Exploring trends in the data

  1. Using data from all sessions, provide a plot that shows the share of female legislators by session!
aut_political <- get_political(legislature ="aut")

aut_core_political <- left_join(aut_core, aut_political, by = "pageid")

session_female_share <- 
  aut_core_political %>% 
  group_by(session) %>% 
  summarize(female_share = mean(sex == "female"))

ggplot(session_female_share, aes(x = session, y = female_share)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "blue") +
  labs(x = "Session of Parliament", y = "Share of Female Politicians (in %)",
       title = "Figure 2: Share of Female Politicians in Austrian Parliament") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

I decided to explore the change in the share of females in the Austrian Nationalrat according to party affiliation starting 1945 until today.

Limitations The 5th session of parliament was the first after the second world war. Given a very different composition of parties in the Nationalrat before session 5, it was decided to exclude session 1 to 4 from this analysis.

The two major parties: VP and SP The two major Austrian Parties, the conservative VP and the left-leaning SP, first emerged in the 1945 election and dominated Austrian politics from the 5th until the 15th session of the Nationalrat. We observe that the share of famales was substantially higher in the SP compared to the VP. From the 5th until the 15th session, the share of female politicians averaged around 3.9% in the VP and 9.7% in the SP. We observe that the share of females was substantially higher in the SP compared to the VP. This relativly higher share can also be observed from session 16 onwards while both parties (finally) increased their female share. From session 16 to 27, the VP had an average female share of 23% and the SP of 32%. Two new parties: Green and FP During the 16th and 17th session, two new political parties entered the ring the could hardly be more different: the left-wing Greens and the ultra-conservative FP. Upon analyzing Figure 3 one observes that across the years the Green Party consistently had the highest female share avergaing 50% since they first joined parliament during the 17th session. The FP which joined parliament during the 16th session varied in its female share but averaged rather low around 18.6%

The most recent addition to parilament: NEOS During the 25th session of the Nationalrat the liberal NEOS party was part of the Nationalrat for the first time. Its female share averaged around 41.1%. It is thus the party with the highest share of females after the Greens.

Summary and Outlook All in all, the share of females in increased over the years. While the share of females has increased among the traditional parties VP and SP, it is in particular the newer parties, Green and NEOS with their high female share, that have substantially helped increase the female share of the entire parliament. Given that the Nationalrat currently has a female share of just below 40% (see 2a) we have come a long way from 5.9% during its first session, but we still have some way to go in order to have a parliament that has the same share of females as society has.
